Note: in Desktop mode, press "3" to equip the Protoflux tool
1.  With the Protoflux tool equipped, grab the "Hours" slot
Note: in Desktop mode, press CTRL+T to open the Context Menu
2.  Open the Context Menu and select "Unpack"  
3.  Grab a "Minute" node and place it in front of the "Hour" node
4.  Connect the "User Time" node's output to the input of the "Minute" node
5.  Grab a "Divide (รท)" node and place it to the right of the "Minute" node
Note: in Desktop mode, press SHIFT+R after pulling out a connector to create a "Display" or "Input" node
6.  Pull out the bottom input of the "Minute" node and and secondary click to create an "int Input" node
7.  Set the value to "60"
8.  Connect the output of the "Divide" node to the bottom input of the "Multiply" node FIRST.
Note: it is VERY IMPORTANT to connect this way first, so that the output of the "Multiply" node will be a float (a number that can have decimal places), instead of an integer (a whole number)
9.  Grab an "Add (+)" node and place it to the right of the "Divide" node
10. Connect the output of the "Divide" node to the bottom input of the "Add" node
11. Connect the output of the Modulo node to the top input of the "Add" node
12. Reposition nodes if necessary, then connect the input of the "Multiply" node to the output of the "Add" node.
Note: in Desktop mode, target any node and press and hold CTRL+R to select all of the nodes
13. Secondary click-and-hold on any of the nodes to select all of the nodes
14. Open the Context menu and select "Pack In Place"
Congratulations!  Your clock is now complete!
